import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.image as mpimg

# Build lists of (image_path, label)
image_paths = []
labels = []

for cat in categories:
    folder = os.path.join(DATA_DIR, cat, "images")  # <--- changed from base_path/cat to DATA_DIR/cat/images
    print("Collecting from:", folder)
    images = [
        f for f in os.listdir(folder)
        if f.lower().endswith((".png", ".jpg", ".jpeg"))
    ]
    for img in images:
        image_paths.append(os.path.join(folder, img))
        labels.append(cat)

# Convert to arrays (for random indexing)
X_paths = np.array(image_paths)
y_labels = np.array(labels)

print("Total images collected:", len(y_labels))

# Guard in case something is still wrong

    print("No images found. Check DATA_DIR, categories, and folder structure.")
else:
    # Randomly pick samples
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, 5, figsize=(12, 6))
    for i in range(2):

            idx = np.random.randint(0, len(y_labels))
            img = mpimg.imread(X_paths[idx])
            ax[i, j].imshow(img, cmap="gray")

            ax[i, j].axis("off")

    plt.suptitle("Sample Chest X-ray Images from the Dataset", fontsize=16)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Checking if dataset is balanced across classes

plt.bar(image_counts.keys(), image_counts.values(), color=['red','green','orange','blue'])

plt.ylabel("Number of Images")
plt.xticks(rotation=15)

  • The dataset is heavily imbalanced as seen in the bar chart displayed above. The 'Normal image' class is the majority class, representing almost half of the sample. It is important to address this imbalance before moving on with deep learning as the imbalance may introduce bias to the model.
  • We will implement data augmentation and class weighting to address this imbalance. Data augmentation increases the diversity of training samples for minority classes by applying random transformations, helping the model generalize better. Class weighting adjusts the loss function so that errors on minority classes are penalized more heavily, ensuring the model learns from all categories fairly without discarding valuable data.

To study the impact of imbalance on model performance, we trained two versions of the model:

  1. A baseline model trained on the original (imbalanced) data.
  2. A balanced model trained after applying data augmentation and class weighting.

def make_datasets(data_dir=DATA_DIR, img_size=IMG_SIZE, batch_size=BATCH_SIZE, seed=SEED):
    """
    Loads images from folders, splits into 80% training, 10% validation, 10% testing.
    Applies normalization to all sets, and augmentation only to training.
    """

    # Putting 80% of images in training
    train_raw = keras.utils.image_dataset_from_directory(
        data_dir,
        validation_split=0.2,
        subset="training",
        seed=seed,
        image_size=img_size,
        batch_size=batch_size,
    )

    # Using 20% left for validation & test
    valtest_raw = keras.utils.image_dataset_from_directory(
        data_dir,
        validation_split=0.2,
        subset="validation",
        seed=seed,
        image_size=img_size,
        batch_size=batch_size,
    )

    # Splitting the 20% into 10% val & 10% test
    card = tf.data.experimental.cardinality(valtest_raw).numpy()
    val_raw  = valtest_raw.take(card // 2)
    test_raw = valtest_raw.skip(card // 2)

    def prep_train(x, y): return augment(norm(x), training=True), y
    def prep_eval(x, y):  return norm(x), y

    train = train_raw.shuffle(512).map(prep_train, num_parallel_calls=AUTOTUNE).prefetch(AUTOTUNE)
    val   = val_raw.map(prep_eval,   num_parallel_calls=AUTOTUNE).prefetch(AUTOTUNE)
    test  = test_raw.map(prep_eval,  num_parallel_calls=AUTOTUNE).prefetch(AUTOTUNE)

    return train, val, test, train_raw.class_names
In[11]:
def compute_class_weight_from_dir(data_dir, class_names, train_frac=0.8):
    import math

    counts_total = {}
    for i, cls in enumerate(class_names):
        folder = os.path.join(data_dir, cls)  # images directly inside
        n = sum(f.lower().endswith((".png", ".jpg", ".jpeg")) for f in os.listdir(folder))
        counts_total[i] = n

    counts_train = {i: max(1, math.floor(n * train_frac)) for i, n in counts_total.items()}

    K = len(counts_train)
    N = sum(counts_train.values())
    class_weight = {i: float(N / (K * n_i)) for i, n_i in counts_train.items()}
    return class_weight
In[12]:
# Building the Model

def make_mobilenet_model(num_classes, img_size=IMG_SIZE, lr=1e-4):
    """
    Creates lightweight CNN model using transfer learning from MobileNetV2.
    - Uses pretrained ImageNet weights
    - Adds small custom classification head
    """
    base = applications.MobileNetV2(include_top=False, weights="imagenet",
                                    input_shape=img_size + (3,))
    base.trainable = False

    # Defining model architecture
    inp = layers.Input(shape=img_size + (3,))
    x = keras.applications.mobilenet_v2.preprocess_input(inp)
    x = base(x, training=False)
    x = layers.GlobalAveragePooling2D()(x)
    x = layers.Dense(128, activation="relu")(x)
    x = layers.Dropout(0.3)(x)
    out = layers.Dense(num_classes, activation="softmax")(x)
    model = keras.Model(inp, out)
    model.compile(optimizer=keras.optimizers.Adam(lr),
                  loss="sparse_categorical_crossentropy",
                  metrics=["accuracy"])
    return model
In[13]:
# Model Evaluation

def evaluate_to_text(tag, model, test_ds, class_names):
    """
    Evaluates trained model on test set.
    Prints: accuracy, classification report, and confusion matrix.
    """

    # Evaluating test performance
    test_loss, test_acc = model.evaluate(test_ds, verbose=0)
    print(f"[{tag}] Test accuracy: {test_acc:.4f}")

    # Converting dataset tensors to numpy arrays
    y_true = np.concatenate([y.numpy() for _, y in test_ds.unbatch().batch(2048)])
    y_prob = model.predict(test_ds, verbose=0)
    y_pred = y_prob.argmax(axis=1)

    # Extracting metrics
    print(f"\n[{tag}] Classification report (TEST):")
    print(classification_report(y_true, y_pred, target_names=class_names, zero_division=0))
    print(f"[{tag}] Confusion matrix (TEST):")
    print(confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred))
    return test_acc

In[15]:
# Experiment Runner (Main Function)

def run_experiment(tag, use_class_weight=False, epochs=5, lr=1e-4):
    """
    Runs full training cycle.
    - 'use_class_weight=False': imbalanced baseline
    - 'use_class_weight=True': balanced (augmentation + weights)
    """

    # Building datasets and model
    train_ds, val_ds, test_ds, class_names = make_datasets()
    model = make_mobilenet_model(len(class_names), lr=lr)

    cw = None
    if use_class_weight:
        cw = compute_class_weight_from_dir(DATA_DIR, class_names)
        print("Class weights:", cw)

    # Training model
    history = model.fit(
        train_ds,
        validation_data=val_ds,
        epochs=epochs,
        class_weight=cw,
        callbacks=[es],
        verbose=1
    )

    # Evaluating results on test data
    acc = evaluate_to_text(tag, model, test_ds, class_names)
    return {"tag": tag, "history": history.history, "test_acc": acc}

Model Performance Results

  • The imbalanced baseline model reached around 48% test accuracy, but this was largely driven by the dominant Normal class. Minority categories such as COVID and Viral Pneumonia were almost completely misclassified, with near-zero recall and F1-scores.
  • After implementing data augmentation and class weighting, the overall accuracy improved slightly to ~53%, and the model demonstrated better recognition of minority classes, particularly Lung Opacity. While the gain in accuracy was modest, this approach reduced bias and improved class-level balance, showing a better trade-off between overall accuracy and fairness across categories.

Reflect on the practical value of this classification task. Who might benefit from your model in a real-world setting?

  • This classification task is valuable in the medical field, especially for doctors and radiologists who analyze chest X-rays. An automated model like this can serve as a decision-support tool, helping doctors quickly screen large numbers of X-ray images and prioritize potentially abnormal cases such as COVID-19 or pneumonia. While not a replacement for professional diagnosis, it can serve as a useful decision-support tool in clinical settings.

# Building CNN model

def build_baseline_cnn(input_shape, num_classes):
    inputs = keras.layers.Input(shape=input_shape)

    x = keras.layers.Conv2D(32, 3, padding="same", use_bias=False)(inputs)
    x = keras.layers.BatchNormalization()(x); x = keras.layers.ReLU()(x)
    x = keras.layers.MaxPool2D()(x)

    x = keras.layers.Conv2D(64, 3, padding="same", use_bias=False)(x)
    x = keras.layers.BatchNormalization()(x); x = keras.layers.ReLU()(x)
    x = keras.layers.MaxPool2D()(x)

    x = keras.layers.Conv2D(128, 3, padding="same", use_bias=False)(x)
    x = keras.layers.BatchNormalization()(x); x = keras.layers.ReLU()(x)
    x = keras.layers.MaxPool2D()(x)

    x = keras.layers.Conv2D(128, 3, padding="same", use_bias=False)(x)
    x = keras.layers.BatchNormalization()(x); x = keras.layers.ReLU()(x)
    x = keras.layers.GlobalAveragePooling2D()(x)

    x = keras.layers.Dropout(0.4)(x)
    x = keras.layers.Dense(128, activation="relu")(x)
    x = keras.layers.Dropout(0.3)(x)
    outputs = keras.layers.Dense(num_classes, activation="softmax")(x)

    model = keras.Model(inputs, outputs)
    model.compile(
        optimizer=keras.optimizers.Adam(1e-3),
        loss="sparse_categorical_crossentropy",
        metrics=["accuracy"]
    )
    return model

Clearly describe the architecture, loss function, optimizer, evaluation metrics, and training configuration.

Architecture:

  • 4 convolutional blocks with BatchNorm ReLU; the first 3 use MaxPool to downsample; the last uses GlobalAveragePooling.
  • Then Dropout(0.4) Dense(128, ReLU) Dropout(0.3) Softmax(num_classes).

Loss function:

  • sparse_categorical_crossentropy, which is suitable for integer-encoded class labels.

Optimizer:

  • Adam with a learning rate of 1e-3, providing adaptive gradient updates for efficient convergence.

Evaluation metrics:

  • Primary metric: accuracy during training and validation.
  • After training, precision, recall, F1-score, and the confusion matrix are reported for a detailed performance breakdown across classes.

Training configuration:

  • Input size: 128128 RGB images (IMG_SIZE + (3,))
  • Batch size: 32
  • Epochs: 3 for faster testing
  • Early stopping is used to prevent overfitting, restoring the best weights when validation loss stops improving.

Report the models training, validation, and test performance.

During training:

  • Final training accuracy: 0.63
  • Final validation accuracy: 0.57
  • Final validation loss: 1.1

On the held-out test set, the model achieved:

  • Test accuracy: 0.56
  • Test loss: 1.04

The baseline CNN shows moderate learning and generalization, capturing key image features but still limited by class imbalance and the simplicity of the architecture.

# Implementing ResNet using transfer learning
def build_resnet_transfer(num_classes, base_trainable=False, input_res=(224, 224)):
    inputs = keras.Input(shape=IMG_SIZE + (3,))  # Your dataset outputs IMG_SIZE
    x = layers.Resizing(input_res[0], input_res[1])(inputs)       # 128->224
    x = layers.Rescaling(scale=2.0, offset=-1.0)(x)               # [0,1] -> [-1,1] for ResNet

    base = ResNet50(weights="imagenet", include_top=False, input_shape=input_res + (3,))
    base.trainable = base_trainable  # freeze for initial transfer learning

    x = base(x)
    x = layers.GlobalAveragePooling2D()(x)
    x = layers.Dropout(0.3)(x)
    x = layers.Dense(256, activation="relu")(x)
    x = layers.Dropout(0.3)(x)
    outputs = layers.Dense(num_classes, activation="softmax")(x)

    model = keras.Model(inputs, outputs, name="resnet50_transfer")
    model.compile(
        optimizer=keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=1e-4),
        loss="sparse_categorical_crossentropy",
        metrics=["accuracy"]
    )
    return model

resnet_tl = build_resnet_transfer(num_classes=num_classes, base_trainable=False)
resnet_tl.summary()

In[24]:
# Unfreeze a few top layers and train with a smaller learning rate
# Define helper to unfreeze top layers
from tensorflow.keras import layers

def unfreeze_top_layers(model, n_layers_to_unfreeze=40):
    """
    Unfreezes the last N layers of the ResNet base (excluding BatchNorm).
    """
    base = None
    for layer in model.layers:
        if "resnet50" in layer.name.lower():
            base = layer
            break
        if hasattr(layer, "layers"):
            for sub in layer.layers:
                if "resnet50" in sub.name.lower():
                    base = sub
                    break
    if base is None:
        raise ValueError("ResNet base not found.")

    # Freeze all layers first, then unfreeze the last N
    for layer in base.layers:
        layer.trainable = False
    for layer in base.layers[-n_layers_to_unfreeze:]:
        if not isinstance(layer, layers.BatchNormalization):
            layer.trainable = True

    return model

Discuss how using pre-trained features influences your model's training and generalization.

Using pre-trained ResNet50 features greatly improved both convergence and generalization. With the base frozen, the model already outperformed the baseline CNN (test accuracy 59% vs 48%). After unfreezing top layers, accuracy rose further to 68%, showing that pre-trained representations provided strong, transferable visual features. These features accelerated learning and reduced overfitting, while fine-tuning allowed domain-specific adaptation to X-ray patterns.

from tensorflow.keras.applications import VGG16
from tensorflow.keras import layers, Model, optimizers
from tensorflow import keras

def build_vgg16(num_classes, input_res=(224,224)):
    inputs = keras.Input(shape=IMG_SIZE + (3,))
    x = layers.Resizing(*input_res)(inputs)
    x = layers.Rescaling(2.0, offset=-1.0)(x)  # [0,1] -> [-1,1]

    base = VGG16(weights="imagenet", include_top=False, input_shape=input_res + (3,))
    base.trainable = False

    x = base(x)
    x = layers.GlobalAveragePooling2D()(x)
    x = layers.Dropout(0.3)(x)
    x = layers.Dense(256, activation="relu")(x)
    x = layers.Dropout(0.3)(x)
    outputs = layers.Dense(num_classes, activation="softmax")(x)
    model = Model(inputs, outputs, name="vgg16_transfer")
    model.compile(optimizer=optimizers.Adam(1e-4),
                  loss="sparse_categorical_crossentropy",
                  metrics=["accuracy"])
    return model

def plot_history(histories, metric="accuracy", figsize=(12, 6)):
    plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    for name, hist in histories.items():
        if metric in hist:
            plt.plot(hist[metric], label=f"{name} (train)")
        if f"val_{metric}" in hist:
            plt.plot(hist[f"val_{metric}"], linestyle="--", label=f"{name} (val)")
    plt.title(f"Training & Validation {metric.title()}")
    plt.xlabel("Epoch")
    plt.ylabel(metric.title())
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

# Accuracy curves
plot_history(histories, metric="accuracy")

# Loss curves
plot_history(histories, metric="loss")

Lastly, the third augmentation was layers.RandomZoom(0.1), it zooms out of the photo by 10%.

The best performing model is still InceptionV3. With 5 epoch, its Val accuracy climbed to 0.7376 with a loss around 67%.
